books.google.com/books?id=gJQP0WUt5Z0C&pg=PA27|accessdate=24 July 2013|year=2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-84070-5|page=27}}</ref><ref name=\"CottaVerzichelli2007\">{{cite book|author1=Maurizio Cotta|author2=Luca Verzichelli|title=Political Institutions in Italy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G-FAZHBDqggC&pg=PA38|accessdate=17 July 2013|year=2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-928470-2|page=38}}</ref><ref>https://ideas.repec.org/a/taf/eujhet/v19y2012i4p587-624.html</ref><ref>http://cronologia.leonardo.it/mondo38m.htm</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fondazione-einaudi.it/Download/lezione_Scognamiglio_2011.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-07-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305023500/http://www.fondazione-einaudi.it/Download/lezione_Scognamiglio_2011.pdf |archive-date=2016-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.luigieinaudi.it/percorsi-di-lettura/lib/la-teoria-politia-di-luigi-einaudi.html</ref><ref>http://magna-carta.it/content/liberalismo-liberismo-e-antistatalismo</ref><br />[[Conservative liberalism]]<br />[[Conservatism]]<ref name=\"Lansford2013\">{{cite book|editor=Tom Lansford|title=Political Handbook of the World 2013|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lUF1AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA714|year=2013|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-4522-5825-6|page=714}}</ref><ref name=\"NanettiLeonardi2014\">{{cite book|author1=Raffaella Y. Nanetti|author2=Robert Leonardi|chapter=Italy|editor1=M. Donald Hancock|editor2=Christopher J. Carman|editor3=Marjorie Castle|editor4=David P. Conradt|editor5=Raffaella Y. Nanetti|editor6=Robert Leonardi|editor7=William Safran|editor8=Stephen White|title=Politics in Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KmAXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA363|year=2014|publisher=CQ Press|isbn=978-1-4833-2305-3|page=363}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Centrism|Centre]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Koff |first1=Sondra Z. |last2=Koff |first2=Stephen P. |title=Italy: From the First to the Second Republic |date=2000 |publisher=Taylor & Francis US |page=40 |quote=Early in the First Republic the PLI had two wings, one of which emphasized its political liberalism and progressive tradition.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Jones |first1=Erik |last2=Pasquino |first2=Gianfranco |title=The Oxford Handbook of Italian Politics |date=2015 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=456}}</ref> to [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]]<ref name=\"NanettiLeonardi2014\"/><ref name=\"Padovani2007\">{{cite book|author=Cinzia Padovani|title=A Fatal Attraction: Public Television and Politics in Italy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aMsiP1HibrkC&pg=PA258|accessdate=18 February 2013|year=2007|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-1950-3|page=258}}</ref>\n| national       = {{Nowrap|[[National Blocs]] (1922\u201324)<br />[[National List (Italy)|National List]] (1924\u201326)<br />[[National Liberation Committee]] (1943\u201346)<br />[[National Democratic Union (Italy)|National Democratic Union]] (1946\u201348)<br />[[National Bloc (Italy)|National Bloc]] (1948)<br />[[Centrism (Italy)|Centrism]] (1948\u20131958)<br />''[[Pentapartito]]''<ref name=\"Il Pentapartito\">[http://www.storiaxxisecolo.it/larepubblica/repubblica10.htm Il Pentapartito - Storia della Repubblica Italiana]</ref> (1980\u20131993)}}\n| international  = [[Liberal International]]\n| european       = [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party|ELDR Party]]\n| europarl       = [[European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group|ELDR Group]]\n| colours        = {{Color box|{{Italian Liberal Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Blue]]\n| country        = Italy\n}}\n\nThe '''Italian Liberal Party''' ({{lang-it|Partito Liberale Italiano}}, '''PLI''') was a [[liberalism|liberal]] and [[conservatism|conservative]] [[List of political parties in Italy|political party in Italy]].\n\nThe PLI, which is the heir of the liberal currents of both the [[Historical Right]] and the [[Historical Left]], was a minor party after [[World War II]], but also a frequent junior party in government, especially since 1979.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\n{{see also|Liberalism and radicalism in Italy}}\n\nThe origins of [[liberalism]] in Italy are in the [[Historical Right]], a parliamentary group formed by [[Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour|Camillo Benso di Cavour]] in the Parliament of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]] following the [[revolutions of 1848 in the Italian states|1848 revolution]]. The group was moderately [[conservatism|conservative]] and supported centralised government, restricted [[suffrage]], [[regressive tax]]ation, and [[free trade]]. They dominated politics following [[Italian unification]] in 1861 but never formed a party, basing their power on [[census suffrage]] and [[first-past-the-post voting]] system.\n\nThe Right was opposed by the more [[progressivism|progressive]] [[Historical Left]], which overthrew [[Marco Minghetti]]'s government during the so-called \"Parliamentary Revolution\" of 1876, which brought [[Agostino Depretis]] to become [[Prime Minister of Italy|Prime Minister]]. However, Depretis immediately began to look for support among Rightists MPs, who readily changed their positions, in a context of widespread [[political corruption|corruption]]. This phenomenon, known in Italian as ''[[trasformismo]]'' (roughly translatable in English as \"transformism\"\u2014in a satirical newspaper, the PM was depicted as a [[chameleon]]), effectively removed political differences in Parliament, which was dominated by an undistinguished liberal bloc with a landslide majority until [[World War I]].\n\nTwo parliamentary factions alternated in government, one led by [[Sidney Sonnino]] and the other, by far the largest of the two, by [[Giovanni Giolitti]]. The latter was known as [[Liberal Union (Italy)|Liberal Union]] since 1913 and was finally re-joined also by Sonnino. At that time the Liberals governed in alliance with the [[Italian Radical Party|Radicals]], the [[Constitutional Democratic Party (Italy)|Democrats]] and, eventually, the [[Italian Reformist Socialist Party|Reformist Socialists]].<ref>[http://concise.britannica.com/ebc/article-9368300/Italian-Liberal-Party Italian Liberal Party] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121013656/http://concise.britannica.com/ebc/article-9368300/Italian-Liberal-Party |date=2006-11-21 }}, Britannica Concise</ref>\n\n===The brief party===\n[[File:Giovanni Giolitti 2.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Giovanni Giolitti]], five-time [[Prime Minister of Italy]] (1892\u20131921)]]\nAt the end of World War I, [[universal suffrage]] and [[proportional representation]] were introduced. These reforms caused big problems to the Liberals, which found themselves unable to stop the rise of two mass parties, the [[Italian Socialist Party]] (PSI) and the [[Italian People's Party (1919)|Italian People's Party]] (PPI), which had taken the control of many local authorities in [[northern Italy]] even before the war. The [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] PPI opposed the PSI, but also the Liberals and, generally, the Right, under the consequences of the [[capture of Rome]] and the struggles between the [[Holy See]] and the Italian state which the Liberals had ruled for more than fifty years.\n\nThe Parliament was thus divided in three different blocks with huge instability, while the Socialists and the rising [[National Fascist Party|Fascists]] instigators of political violence on opposite sides. In this chaotic situation, the Liberals founded the '''Italian Liberal Party''' (PLI) in 1922, which immediately joined an alliance led by Fascists and formed with them a joint list for the [[1924 Italian general election|1924 general election]], transforming the Fascists from a small political force into an absolute-majority party. The PLI was banned by [[Benito Mussolini]] in 1925, while many old Liberal politicians were given prestigious, but not influential, political posts, such as seats in the Senate, which was stripped of any real power by Fascist reforms.\n\n===Post World War II===\n[[File:Luigi Einaudi.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Luigi Einaudi]], [[President of Italy]] from 1948 to 1955]]\nThe PLI was re-founded in 1943 by [[Benedetto Croce]], a prominent intellectual and senator whose international recognition allowed him to remain a free man during the [[Italian Fascism|Fascist regime]], despite being an [[Anti-fascism|anti-fascist]] himself. After the end of [[World War II]], [[Enrico De Nicola]], a Liberal, became \"Provisional Head of State\" and another one, [[Luigi Einaudi]], who as Minister of Economy and Governor of the [[Bank of Italy]] between 1945 and 1948 had reshaped Italian economy, succeeded him as [[President of Italy]].\n\nIn the [[1946 Italian general election|1946 general election]] the PLI, which was part of the [[National Democratic Union (Italy)|National Democratic Union]], won 6.8% of the vote, which was somewhat below expectations. Indeed, the party was supported by all the survivors of the Italian political class before the rise of Fascism, from [[Vittorio Emanuele Orlando]] to [[Francesco Saverio Nitti]]. In the first years, the party was led by [[Leone Cattani]], member of the internal left, and then by [[Roberto Lucifero d'Aprigliano|Roberto Lucifero]], a [[Monarchism|monarchist]]-conservative. This fact caused the exit of the group of Cattani and [[Bruno Villabruna]], a moderate, was elected secretary in 1948 in order to re-unite all the Liberals under a single banner.\n\n===Giovanni Malagodi===\n[[File:Giovanni Malagodi.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Giovanni Malagodi]], Liberal leader from 1954 to 1972]]\nUnder the leadership of [[Giovanni Malagodi]] (1954\u20131972) the party moved further to the right on economic issues. This caused in 1956 the exit of the party's left-wing, including [[Bruno Villabruna]], [[Eugenio Scalfari]] and [[Marco Pannella]], who founded the [[Radical Party (Italy)|Radical Party]]. In particular, the PLI opposed the new centre-left coalition that included also the [[Italian Socialist Party]] and presented itself as the main [[conservatism|conservative]] party in Italy.\n\nMalagodi managed to draw some votes from the [[Italian Social Movement]], the [[Monarchist National Party]] and especially [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democracy]], whose electoral base was composed also by conservatives suspicious of the Socialists, increasing the party's share to a historical record of 7.0% in the [[1963 Italian general election|1963 general election]]. After Malagodi's resignation from the party's leadership, the PLI was defeated with a humiliating 1.3% in [[1976 Italian general election|1976]], but tried to re-gain strength by supporting social reforms such as [[divorce]].\n\n===The ''Pentapartito''===\nAfter [[Valerio Zanone]] took over as secretary in 1976, the PLI adopted a more [[centrism|centrist]] and, to some extent, [[social liberalism|social-liberal]] approach. The new secretary opened to the [[Italian Socialist Party|Socialists]], hoping to put in action a sort of [[Lib\u2013Lab pact|Lib\u2013Lab]] cooperation, similar to that experimented in the [[United Kingdom]] from 1977 to 1979 between the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]]. In 1983 the PLI finally joined the ''[[pentapartito]]'' coalition composed also of the [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democracy]] (DC), the [[Italian Socialist Party]] (PSI), the [[Italian Democratic Socialist Party]] (PSDI) and the [[Italian Republican Party]] (PRI). In the 1980s the party was led by [[Renato Altissimo]] and [[Alfredo Biondi]].\n\nWith the uncovering of the [[political corruption|corruption]] system nicknamed ''Tangentopoli'' by the ''[[Mani pulite]]'' investigation, many government parties experienced a rapid loss of their support. In the first months the PLI seemed immune to investigation. However, as the investigations further unraveled, the party turned out to be part of the corruption scheme. [[Francesco De Lorenzo]], the Liberal [[Italian Minister of Health|Minister of Health]], was one of the most loathed politicians in Italy for his corruption, that involved stealing funds from the sick, and allowing commercialisation of medicines based on bribes.\n\n===Dissolution and diaspora===\nThe party was disbanded on 6 February 1994 and at least four heirs tried to take its legacy: \n*the [[Union of the Centre (1993)|Union of the Centre]] (UdC), led by [[Alfredo Biondi]], [[Raffaele Costa]] and [[Enrico Nan]], was an associate party of [[Forza Italia]] (FI) and was merged into it in 1998 (other Liberals, including [[Antonio Martino]], [[Giuliano Urbani]], [[Giancarlo Galan]] and [[Paolo Romani]], joined directly FI);\n*the [[Italian Liberal Right]] (DLI), led by [[Gabriele Pagliuzzi]] and [[Giuseppe Basini]], joined [[National Alliance (Italy)|National Alliance]] (AN);\n*the [[Federation of Liberals]] (FdL), led by [[Raffaello Morelli]] and [[Valerio Zanone]], first joined the [[Patto Segni]], then [[The Olive Tree (Italy)|The Olive Tree]];\n*the [[Liberal Left]] (SL) of [[Gianfranco Passalacqua]], representing the party's left-wingers, was finally merged into the [[Democrats of the Left]] in 2006.\n\nIn a few years after 1994, most Liberals migrated to FI, while others joined the centre-left, especially [[Democracy is Freedom \u2013 The Daisy]] (DL).\n\n===Re-foundation===\n{{Main|Italian Liberal Party (1997)}}\n\nThe party was re-founded in 1997 by [[Stefano De Luca]] and re-took its original name in 2004. The new PLI gathered some of the former right-wing Liberals, but soon distanced itself from the centre-right coalition, led by FI, in order to follow an autonomous path.\n\n==Popular support==\nBefore World Wars the Liberals constituted the political establishment that governed Italy for decades. They had their main bases in [[Piedmont]], where many leading liberal politicians of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]] and the [[Kingdom of Italy]] came from, and [[southern Italy]]. The Liberals never gained large support after [[World War II]] as they were not able to become a mass party and were replaced by [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democracy]] (DC) as the dominant political force. In the [[1946 Italian general election|1946 general election]], the first after the war, the PLI gained 6.8% as part of the [[National Democratic Union (Italy)|National Democratic Union]]. At that time they were strong especially in the South, as DC was mainly rooted in the [[Northern Italy|North]]: 21.0% in [[Campania]], 22.8% in [[Basilicata]], 10.4% in [[Apulia]], 12.8% in [[Calabria]] and 13.6% in [[Sicily]].<ref>Piergiorgio Corbetta; Maria Serena Piretti, ''Atlante storico-elettorale d'Italia'', Zanichelli, [[Bologna]] 2009</ref>\n\nHowever, the party soon found its main constituency in the industrial elites of the \"industrial triangle\" formed by [[Turin]], [[Milan]] and [[Genoa]]. The PLI had its best results in the 1960s, when it was rewarded by conservative voters for their opposition to the participation of the [[Italian Socialist Party]] (PSI) in government. The party won 7.0% of the vote in [[1963 Italian general election|1963]] (15.2% in Turin, 18.7% in Milan and 11.5% in Genoa) and 5.8% [[1963 Italian general election|1963]]. The PLI suffered a decline in the 1970s and settled around 2\u20133% in the 1980s, when its strongholds were reduced to Piedmont, especially the [[Province of Turin|provinces of Torino]] and [[Province of Cuneo|Cuneo]], and, to a minor extent, western Lombardy, Liguria and Sicily.<ref name=\"Interno\">http://elezionistorico.interno.it/index.php?tp=C</ref>\n\nAs the other parties of the ''[[pentapartito]]'' coalition (Christian Democrats, [[Italian Socialist Party|Socialists]], [[Italian Republican Party|Republicans]] and [[Italian Democratic Socialist Party|Democratic Socialists]]), the Liberals strengthened their grip on the South, while in the North they lost some of their residual votes to [[Lega Nord]] and its precursors. In the [[1992 Italian general election|1992 general election]], the last before the ''[[Mani pulite|Tangentopoli]]'' scandals, the PLI won 2.9% of the vote, largely thanks to the increase of votes from the South.<ref name=Interno/> After the end of the \"[[History of Italy as a Republic#The \"First Republic\" (1948\u20131992)|First Republic]]\" former Liberals were very influent within [[Forza Italia]] (FI) in Piedmont, Liguria and, strangely enough, in [[Veneto]], where [[Giancarlo Galan]] was three times elected [[President of Veneto|President]].\n\nThe electoral results of the PLI in general ([[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)|Chamber of Deputies]]) and [[European Parliament]] elections since 1913 are shown in the chart below.\n\n{{Graph:Chart|width=735|type=rect|colors=#2975C2\n|xAxisTitle=Elections\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=Nov. 1913, Nov. 1919, May 1921, Apr. 1924, Mar. 1929, Mar. 1934, Jun. 1946, Apr. 1948, Jun. 1953, May 1958, Apr. 1963, May 1968, May 1972, Jun. 1976, 3 Jun. 1979, 10 Jun. 1979, Jun. 1983, Jun. 1984, Jun. 1987, Jun. 1989, Apr. 1992, Mar. 1994, Jun. 1994\n|yAxisTitle=% of popular vote\n|y=47.6, 8.6, 7.1, 3.3, 0.0, 0.0, 6.8, 3.8, 3.0, 3.5, 7.0, 5.8, 3.9, 1.3, 1.9, 3.6, 2.9, 6.1, 2.1, 4.4, 2.9}}\n\n==Electoral results==\n\n===Italian Parliament===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"width:50%; border:1px #AAAAFF solid\"\n|-\n| colspan=6|[[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)|Chamber of Deputies]]\n|-\n! width=13%|Election year\n! width=16%|Votes\n! width=6%|% \n! width=1%|Seats\n! width=8%|+/\u2212\n! width=18%|Leader\n|-\n! [[1913 Italian general election|1913]]\n| 2,387,947 (1st)\n| 47.6\n| {{Composition bar|270|508|hex={{Italian Liberal Party/meta/color}}}}\n| <center>\u2013</center>\n| <center>[[Giovanni Giolitti]]</center>\n|-\n! [[1919 Italian general election|1919]]\n| 490,384 (5th)\n| 8.6\n| {{Composition bar|41|508|hex={{Italian Liberal Party/meta/color}}}}\n| <center>{{decrease}} 229</center>\n| <center>[[Giovanni Giol